segments.text: Mike is working.
This is July 30.
Right.
Seated in the beautifully decorated and awfully neat living room of Howard Perry's.
Going to chat about his days at A&M.
Test your mic now.
All right.
Can you hear what I'm saying?
I do.
I always, when I listen to my own voice, I always think it sounds terrible.
Tell, for the person that might read or listen to, read the transcription or hear the tape, begin by giving us a brief summary of your experience before you first came to A&M as a student.
Well, I actually was born in Milwaukee, Wisconsin.
And I always tell everybody, as soon as I could walk, I came to Texas.
That's not quite true.
But I came to Texas when I was about six years old, I guess.
It was in 1928 or 29.
I'm not sure of the exact year.
Then I moved into a little town called Spearman in the panhandle of Texas.
My father was...
And he was the manager of the Ford place there.
And he also, on the side, did some repair work on refrigeration, which a lot of people had some refrigerators, but not a whole lot.
And I went through grade school and high school there.
Well, my father died.
I spent about a year out of Spearman, and I went to school in St. Louis, Missouri, in one of their schools, and then came back to Spearman, because Mother then got some work back there.
This was during the hard times.
I went on to high school, and we— Well, you lived in Cuba for a year.
That was during that period of time, too.
Anyway, I came back, as I said, and went to school, high school and all, and graduated from high school.
Spearman was a very small school.
I think there were sixty-eight in a graduating class, if that many.
But I decided I wanted to go to Oklahoma A&M.

And so I went over there one summer because we didn't have solid geometry and chemistry in Spearman, and I wanted to take that solid geometry and chemistry in a summer session, which I thought would be a little better.
But I came home from there, and...

I got ready to go back to Oklahoma A&M, but I'd been talking to a couple of my friends, one that was going to be a sophomore down here at A&M, and the other very close friend of mine was coming down here as a freshman.
So we got in the car that morning to go to Oklahoma A&M, and I told my mother, I said, you know, I think I'd rather go to Texas A&M.
Well, she just did a right turn, and we came down here.
unannounced.
And they went to the registrar's office, which was down in the Koch building, and I arranged to get my transcripts in there, but they let me come in.
Wait, you said Koch building.
Koch building was... Not Koch building, the administration building.
Yeah, excuse me.
The administration building.
Do you know what year that was?
Yeah, that was in 1940.
Okay.
And I couldn't get a dormitory room,
I find a project house at the North Gate that I could live in.
And this, my mother left me standing on a corner on a Friday before Monday when all the kids came back.
This is in the fall.
September.
Do you remember what, describe what gear, clothing and everything, what all did you bring?
Well,
Of course, I brought underwear and towels and stuff like that and a little bit of civilian clothing.
I don't think I had a suit.
Yeah, I guess I did have a suit and a couple of shirts.
But before Mother left, she bought me what I needed.
We had to buy a lot of our uniforms in those days.
They issued some, but the rest we had to buy.
And shoes and socks and stuff like that.
And she arranged for me to...
going to Penny's in Bryan, and I could sign a check for her name by me there.
That's the only place, if I bought something I needed in the way of clothing.
And that was an unusual experience.
I'll tell you, I was so lonesome.
And then when my room, the guy from Spearman I was going to room with came in on Sunday,
And the other guys began to come in, too, at the project house, and of course they divided, I don't know, I'm sure people have told you about the project house.
We divided up the work and everything and took the bills at the end of the month and split that by however many.
Now, what bills were there?
Well, they had the utility bills, food bills, and I'm sure the bills for paying this woman that ran and cooked the things, because we did the dishes and all.
She was a hard worker.
She wasn't anybody's aunt or grandmother?
No, no.
She may have owned the house.
I don't know.
No, but I've heard in some cases a widow or an aunt or a grandmother might come and be the chief cook, but that wasn't true.
Not that I'm aware of.
Was the whole house from Spearman?
No, no.
There's only two of us from Spearman.
I don't know.
They were from all over, but I mean...
Man, the minute the sophomores get there, we began to catch it.
My roommate and I kept one another in school practically on a nightly basis.
I'd want to go home one night and he didn't want to go home.
The next night he'd want to go home and I didn't want to go home.
But once we got by Thanksgiving, that was all over.
What was it in those first weeks that caused you to be homesick?
Well, you know, I've been away from home so far, and I was an only child.
That's another thing.
And the hazing was in the project house.
I don't know.
It was bad in the core, too, but it was just about as bad in the project house.
And, of course, we caught it when we got on the campus, too.
What...
Give some examples of the hazing you endured.
Well, they beat our fanny regularly.
And I tell you, it was, and I was a skinny kid, and it really hurt.
But then, and they had a ritual that when you were on the campus, walking across the campus,
you saw one of your upperclassmen, you had to speak to him and call him by name.
Now, later on, when I got into the Corps, that turned out pretty good because if he was with a young lady, he was obligated to introduce us to the young lady, see?
But they hadn't, it was just completely changed.
And the school,
My courses were, and I remember I came from a very, very small high school, and I wanted to be an engineer, which was a mistake.
Freshman registration was in Sbisa?
No.
We got our registration cards out in front of the old assembly building, and we picked those up, and we visited all of the departments that we were going to take a course in.
and tried to work our schedule out.
And then we, of course, were assigned to a unit in the Corps.
We had to get that in.
And that was all done by somebody there in the administration.
We didn't know who the heck it was.
So that you were in a Corps unit that first semester, but you lived in the project house.
Did anybody treat you differently because of that arrangement?
Well, we were day ducks, even though we lived like that.

When we came on the campus, we had to wear a campaign hat, and we stood out like a sore thumb because the kids that lived on the campus, they didn't wear headgear on the campus unless they were going to military science.
How would they pick on you then for it?
Well, you know, they'd ask us questions and then they'd ask us when we didn't, you know, they'd stop, you better dang sure introduce yourself to them.
And then you had to ask them where they were from and what their major was and supposed to remember that, you know.
And they didn't haze us physically on the campus.
Mm-hmm.
from being in a project house.
As you look back on it now, who were some important people for you in that first semester?
Of course, my roommate.
Friends or faculty?
I really, I had Dutch Holm.
and for Algebra I.
And I don't remember.
I think Paul Mason may, I'm not sure, may have been a mechanical drawing.
And I didn't take chemistry, the first year of chemistry.
I don't remember.
Ralph Steen was a Texas history teacher.
We didn't have a textbook because he was just written one, you know, and it hadn't been published.
And my association mostly was with there, and a woman that ran this, bless her heart, I can't remember her name, the project house,
You know, it was kind of the one that kept us going.
Did you live there all year?
No, I left there, and I left at the end of the fall semester because I ran out of money.
The house ran out of money?
No, I did.
Oh, you did.
Oh, so it cost, do you move to the Corps then?
No, no, I left A&M and went to work.
Do you remember what that first semester cost in round numbers?
Well, we paid them articulation fee of $50.
Okay.
And I think we had a laundry fee of not very much, but they do your clothes once a week with so many pieces.
And my room and board, the lowest I remember was about $15 a month.
The highest was about $25.
My memory may be a little vague on that.
And...
Anyway, then I left the first semester, and then I came back.
I still had to do my fifth year, the second half of it.
I came in September.
Of 41.
Right.
That was something.
So you were away for nine months.
How much money did you bring with you that second fall?
Enough to register and pay my, my, uh, my articulation fee and, and mother took care of the, they call it subsistence, for the room and board.
Right, right.
You had gone home and worked?
Yeah, I worked in Spearman and I worked with my aunt in, in Alabama.
How did you get back that second year?
Did somebody drive you, or did you hitchhike?
I don't know that I, I think mother brought me and left me, because she was gone away, which we moved out of Spearman and went on to Amarillo, I mean to Alabama with my aunt.
Because on the motor transportation, using your thumb.
All right, that second year, you're in what outfit?
B-field artillery.
And where were they?
In the New Dorm area?
No, they were over in the old Darm area.
They called it, the new Darm area was being built.
Oh, okay.
I want to say I was in, I can't remember whether it was 6th or 8th.
I think it was 6th.
I think it was Darm 6th.
Tell me about your outfit.
Oh, B-field and
We had a bunch of good guys, and my classmates, there's some of them are dead now.

Dick Hill, we called him Senator Hill, and Forrest Sharp, he got killed during the war, and McIntyre, Don McIntyre, whose daddy was a colonel down here at one time, he got killed during the war, and Earl C. from Waxahachie, and Harold Abona,
from U Valley, and Richard Phillips from Dallas.
Now, the class of 1940 then wasn't very close with the class of 41, or 42, because they gave us a hard time.
Even sophomores, they aged us pretty good at 42, did.
But they were the, that was then, we,
We had, you know, the usual pranks we'd pull.
Such as?
Describe them.
Well, a drowned out is some of them, and they called it, I told Dolores this I think several times, a float out, which is you just gave somebody a hard time.
It didn't have to be true or anything else.
But you had to be detailed to do that.
And the only way you could do it is if you could float out a sophomore, for example, if a junior or senior told you.
And you could float out a junior if a senior told you.
Now, this worked even, sophomores sometimes are caught part of this.
But I remember there was a guy, Pat Murphy,
And he had a date one of the weekends.
This was before, I think, before I met Dolores.
Anyway, she was eating in the dining hall, and this freshman sitting across from him just kept staring at this woman.
It was obvious that he was staring at her.
And finally he turned to Murphy and he said, Mr. Murphy, I don't think your girl has a bad complexion.
Boy.
Everybody knew what happened, of course.
He began to apologize to the girl, and finally the guy that detailed it came up and said that.
All right, now, a float-out, was that a drown-out with more water?
Well, most of the time it really was.
They put it in the room.
Okay.
But we didn't do that.
We drowned out more than we floated out.
What other pranks did y'all try?
Well, it was always...
That flowed out and things like that.
I don't remember too many other pranks.
Did any of your friends put an animal in somebody else's room or move their car up in the hallway?
No.
They only needed cars to speak up.
Do you remember any pranks, whether they involved you or not, do you remember any pranks that in fact were destructive?
No.
So a drown-out... Well, if you got too much in it, it would run down to the room, through the holes around the radiator, and we were very careful about that, not to get too much.
All right, now, so if you and your buddies drowned somebody out, then they would have to take their mattress and put it out in the sun.
That's right.
We did, yeah.
Or did the freshmen get to do that for them?
Well, if they were up there, freshmen probably did it.
And they used to beat their mattresses regularly to soften them up and air them out.
Then, as the Lord said, I had a blind date and went to Brenham on the 4th of July and met her.
And I don't remember, was I a junior when I met you?
Yeah.
I think I was a junior then.
Who helped arrange this?
Well, I think it was Willie Zappalack that got me there.
Willie Zappalack, Charlie Moccamel.
And Charlie Moccamel.
That was another one in my outfit from Brenham I didn't mention.
He and I, we're still very close friends.
I'm with Charlie Moccamel, Harold Abona, and Dick Phillips.
And where did you go on that first date?
Well, there was a very famous spot over there in Brenham, and when I met her, I went up to get her at the door.
We got to the car, and she announced, we're going to the wagon wheel.
What's the wagon wheel?
It was a place all of the high school and college, not a lot of college kids would come to you, particularly on Saturday night, because it was a big place.
They served beer, and they had a jukebox, and we danced.
And we had a good time there.
When you talk about destructive, there was one thing that happened there one night that had no relation to us, but this one fellow I called Forrest Sharp, we called him Feedy.
He was the most likable guy in the world, but you'd get a few beers in him, he got belligerent as hell.
And there was the Navy then came into A&M.
And some of those sailors were over there, and he decided, he went over and mouthed off at them, and they decided they were going to beat him up.
And he ran out and went through the window to get away from them, and the police caught him.
He caused a riot.
Anyway, that's another story, I guess.
All right, and for you and your buddies, was it unusual for you all to drink beer on a date or a night out?
Yeah, because we didn't have too much money.
I never had a beer until I tasted beer up in the Pan Pan.
Spearman was dry as the Sahara Desert.
Somebody, a friend of ours, had some beer in there, and I know one of the boys, and I tasted it.
I didn't like it.
But I came down here and then part of the rituals, I think this was before I left, they took us out to Nezzy's and got us beer.
Was it Nezzy's?
I know you weren't there, but there were two places out there that we used to go to.
You only went to one, I think.
Well, there was Franklin's, and then, of course, the famous place, what was the name of the place?
Mr. Ed?
Navels, Navels.
Huh?
Was it Navels?
No, the one out at College Station that had sold out.
Oh, Uncle Ed's.
Uncle Ed's.
Yeah.
That was the famous, that's where the kids hung out.
Hardlickers.
But they didn't have dancehall.
They didn't have much beer because they didn't have much money.
They didn't have that's all.
So drunkenness was seldom a problem in the dorm?
Oh yeah, very, very, very seldom.
In the dorms, we sometimes hid with some of the guys that had their, you know, had a bottle of maybe a pipe or something like that.
They tried to hide that.
And we had some very ingenious ways.
And when I became a tack officer, it paid off.

You'd pull a medicine cabinet out of the wall and take a wire or string and wrap it around the bottle top, the neck of the bottle, drop it down on the wall and then fasten it there and then put the medicine cabinet back.
Nobody would find it.
And under the shoe rack, they'd try that.
But they didn't have...
there wasn't drunkenness.
When they came in at night, if they were a little bit rowdy, the senior that was on duty, boy, got them quiet and in their sacks.
So that partly the reason they didn't drink or party more was they didn't have the money.
So the girls didn't want you to drink.
They didn't mind if you had a beer, but she and most of her friends, if you got more than two, that was too much.
And, of course, when we came to the dances here on the campus, we didn't have a drink then.
And intermissions, we went down to the two drugstores down at the North Gate.
Yeah, Kennedy's and Lipscomb's, wasn't it?
And had a Coke.
And had a Coke.
Because they didn't serve anything but punch at that time.
You all started going fairly steady while you were students.
Yeah.
Describe the routine for a young man and his date at one of the big A&M dances.
Well, there was not much you can add to it.
There were a number of major dances.
They had what they call a regimental ball, and these were always on a Friday night.
And then Saturday night was a core dance that was open to anybody in the core.
And then you had your class dances, and then after them they had a core dance.
And so these were big affairs.
And the girls all came dressed in evening dresses.
And when you got your gal inside, now the only people that could wear a suit were seniors.
Everybody else had to wear a uniform.
And the seniors wore a uniform a lot of times just so they liked to show off their boots, particularly when they were new.
But when we would come in,
I'd tell Dolores, before we ever got into the, the dancers were all held in the main floor of Sabisa, and there were chairs all around the wall.
That was the only place to sit.
They didn't have tables in there.
I'd tell her, I'd say, now at intermission, I want to meet you here or someplace we made off at intermission.
Because I'd start dancing with her, and when I'd get too far, they had a big stag line down the center, and boy, I was,
be tagged, and the protocol was that I couldn't tag the guy back.
I had to wait around until somebody else tagged him, and then I could tag in.
So it was wonderful times, and they had good bands.
Like Jan Garber, big name bands.
Tommy Dorsey.
There were hardly any places for them to get a room in a motel or hotel for the day.
And, of course, I doubt whether my parents would have even let me come for that.
But they would vacate a dormitory.
And I think it cost the fellas 50 cents a night.
And for the girls, it was just wonderful.
There was a house mother there.
And if they got you in too late, they had to meet a kangaroo court.
They did.
When you would go to Brenham to pick up this young lady,
And did you have a car by then?
No, she came over on the bus last time I rode with one of her friends.
No, I didn't have a car.
All right, what time did the dances and the social events end in the evening?
We have an intermission, and usually they ended, I think, around 1 o'clock, wasn't it?
And the girls had to be in the dormitory room 30 minutes after the dance closed.
Okay.
I can remember that we went to midnight yell practice on Friday night, and we went down there in our uniforms and the girls in their evening dresses for midnight, and even bonfire.
They had a dance before bonfire, and I remember going to bonfire that way.
Do you remember much at the dances?
Do you remember any rowdiness?
Anybody getting drunk, fights at the dances?
No, I don't.
Do you, honey?
I don't remember anybody getting out of line.
There's a picture in one of the annuals.
Everybody was very modest, but this one girl was in.
She was quite well endowed, and she had a midriff.
Evening Down.
What was that guy's name?
It's from Beaumont.
There was a bunch of them came to school here.
Oh, the...
He was the general and one of them became a general.
Oh, for...
It's a Lebanese name.
So-and-so brothers.
Yeah.
Anyway... Kokinos.
Kokinos.
C-O-K-I-N-O-S. Kokinos.
There's a picture in there.
annual of him on his knees in Sebesa looking up at this gal in that dress, and it wasn't his date.
But anyway, I don't remember of any round that.
For one thing, there were a number of faculty members that would go.
Now this was officially a dry county for whiskey.
Yes.
Did you know of a, was there a well-known bootlegger?
No, there was what we called Whiskey Bridge.
And I don't know, the only way you could get any hard liquor, which was dang seldom, you could go down to Whiskey Bridge and that guy ran that.
Well, that was, I think, Briscoe owned that liquor store there.
Yeah.
Was there any, did the students know of any red light district?
In Bryan and Brown?
In Bryan and Brazos County?
I've never heard of any.
No, we didn't.
The only red light district that I, two of them that I'd heard about, one was the Chicken Ranch in LaGrange.
Did, as far as you know, did the Chicken Ranch exist in your day?
I think it did, because they talked about it, some of them did.
And there was one over in Brenham that sometimes the kids would talk about.
I don't know about it.
Huh?
I say I don't know about it.
It was Trixie's or I don't remember what the name of it was.
What did you and your friends know about what today we would call drugs?
You know, if you were a guy or something, you were a drug, you were a... Did you know?
We had a name for them.
Not a drug addict, but... Did you even know the word heroin or marijuana?
Not that I know of.
I heard of marijuana, I think, but I never knew anybody that ever had it.
Did the typical Aggie male smoke?
An awful lot of them did, yeah.
I know I started smoking a pipe because I thought that looked so good.
I could never keep it going.
But I didn't start smoking then.
And did any of your buddies chew?
Like in my day, I'm slightly younger than you but not much, we thought chewing tobacco was country.
Yeah, I don't remember anybody chewing.
